        contentMd: "# Sex Hormones & Contraceptives - Clinical\n\n## Combined Oral Pill Use\n**Starting**: Day 1 of menses (immediate protection)\n**Dosing**: One tablet daily, preferably same time\n**Duration**: 21 days active, 7 days placebo\n**Extended cycles**: 84 days active followed by 7-day break (reduces menstruation)\n**Missed dose**: If <12 hours, take immediately; if >12 hours, guidance depends on cycle position\n\n## Advantages of Combined Pill\n- Effective, reversible\n- Regular, lighter, less painful periods\n- Acne improvement\n- Reduces ovarian/endometrial cancer risk\n- Improves bone density\n\n## Side Effects and Management\n**Nausea**: Take with food, reduce estrogen dose\n**Headaches**: Evaluate for migraine aura (contraindication)\n**Breast tenderness**: Time-limited, take with food\n**Breakthrough bleeding**: Increase pill concentration or change formulation\n**Weight changes**: Usually <2 kg, multifactorial\n\n## Contraindications to COC\n**Absolute**: Age >35 + smoking, migraine with aura, history of VTE/stroke, major surgery with immobility\n**Relative**: Mild liver disease, controlled hypertension, diabetes with complications\n\n## Copper IUD\n**Insertion**: Can insert any time if not pregnant\n**Duration**: 10-12 years\n**Advantages**: No hormones, immediate protection, long-acting\n**Side effects**: Heavier periods, increased cramping, expulsion (2-10%)\n**Contraindication**: Anatomic abnormality, current STI/PID\n\n## LNG-IUD (Mirena)\n**Duration**: 5-7 years\n**Benefits**: Reduced bleeding (40% amenorrhea by year 5)\n**Advantages**: Therapeutic for heavy menstrual bleeding\n**Side effects**: Irregular bleeding first months, then amenorrhea\n\n## Implant (Etonogestrel)\n**Duration**: 3 years\n**Insertion**: Subdermal, upper arm\n**Efficacy**: >99%\n**Advantage**: Set and forget, no daily compliance\n**Disadvantage**: Irregular bleeding, cost, removal required\n\n## Injectable Contraceptive (DMPA - Depo-Provera)\n**Injection**: Every 12 weeks IM\n**Efficacy**: >99% with perfect use, 94% typical\n**Advantages**: High efficacy, private\n**Disadvantages**: Delayed return to fertility (up to 12 months), irregular bleeding, weight gain\n**Return to fertility**: 10 months average\n\n## Fertility Awareness Methods\n**Symptothermal**: BBT + cervical mucus + calendar\n**Efficacy**: 90% typical use\n**Advantages**: No side effects, acceptable religiously\n**Disadvantages**: Requires training, daily monitoring\n\n## Male Sterilization (Vasectomy) vs Female (Tubal Ligation)\n**Effectiveness**: >99% both\n**Reversibility**: Difficult, expensive\n**Procedure**: Outpatient for vasectomy, laparoscopic for tubal\n**Recovery**: Quicker for vasectomy (1 week vs 2 weeks)",
