        contentMd: "# Sex Hormones & Contraceptives - Exam Prep\n\n## Contraceptive Efficacy Ranking\n| Method | Theoretical | Typical |\n|--------|------------|----------|\n| Copper IUD | 0.8 | 0.8 |\n| LNG-IUD | 0.1 | 0.1 |\n| Implant | 0.05 | 0.05 |\n| Injectable | 0.05 | 3-6 |\n| COC | 0.3 | 9 |\n| POP | 0.3 | 9 |\n| Condom | 2 | 18 |\n| Diaphragm | 6 | 12 |\n| Fertility awareness | 5 | 24 |\n\n## Estrogen Dose Classification\n**Ultra-low**: <20 μg ethinyl estradiol\n**Low**: 20-35 μg\n**Standard**: 50 μg (rarely used now)\n\n## Pill Formulations\n**Monophasic**: Same hormone amount all 21 days\n**Biphasic**: Two different hormone levels\n**Triphasic**: Three hormone levels (attempts to mimic natural cycle)\n**Extended**: 84 active pills, 7 placebo (reduces menstruation)\n\n## Progestin-Only Pill Characteristics\n**Mechanism**: Mainly cervical mucus (no ovulation suppression)\n**Timing**: Must take within 3-hour window\n**Advantage**: Safe in lactation, no estrogen side effects\n**Disadvantage**: Frequent breakthrough bleeding, strict timing\n**Return to fertility**: Immediate\n\n## IUD Insertion Timing\n**Copper IUD**: Anytime if not pregnant, up to 5 days post-unprotected intercourse (emergency)\n**LNG-IUD**: Preferably within 7 days of menses\n**Effective immediately**: If inserted in first 7 days of cycle\n**Otherwise**: 7 days of backup contraception\n\n## Common Drug Interactions with COC\n**Antibiotics**: Rifampicin induces metabolism (reduce efficacy)\n**Anticonvulsants**: Phenytoin, carbamazepine (reduce efficacy)\n**Antifungals**: Griseofulvin (reduce efficacy)\n**Note**: Most antibiotics don't significantly interact\n\n## Red Flags Requiring Immediate Consultation\n**ACHES criteria**: \n- **A**bdominal pain (severe)\n- **C**hest pain, dyspnea\n- **H**eadaches (worst ever)\n- **E**ye problems (vision loss, blurred)\n- **S**evere calf pain (DVT)\n\n## Cancer Prevention\n**Endometrial**: Reduced by 50% with COC\n**Ovarian**: Reduced by 40% with COC\n**Cervical**: Increased risk (need screening)\n**Breast**: Slightly increased during use, normalizes 5 years post-stop\n**Colorectal**: No significant effect\n\n## Special Populations\n**Lactation**: POPs, LNG-IUD, copper IUD safe\n**Post-abortion**: Can start immediately\n**Post-partum**: 3 weeks non-lactating, 6 months lactating\n**Adolescents**: LARC preferred due to efficacy\n**Perimenopause**: May reduce hot flashes, improve bone density",
