        contentMd: "# Anxiety Disorders - Exam Prep\n\n## DSM-5 Diagnostic Criteria Summary\n**GAD**: Excessive worry 6+ months + ≥3 symptoms\n**Panic**: Recurrent unexpected panic attacks + ≥1 month anticipatory anxiety\n**Social Anxiety**: Fear of social situations + fear of evaluation + avoidance\n**Specific Phobia**: Persistent, irrational fear + avoidance\n\n## GAD-7 Scoring (High-Yield)\n**Score 0-4**: Minimal\n**Score 5-9**: Mild\n**Score 10-14**: Moderate\n**Score ≥15**: Severe\n\n## SSRI Comparative Efficacy\n**All SSRIs approximately equally effective** for anxiety\n**Differences**: Side effect profiles, drug interactions\n**Sertraline**: Well-tolerated, first-choice\n**Escitalopram**: Fewer drug interactions\n**Paroxetine**: More GI side effects, withdrawal issues\n\n## Benzodiazepine Facts\n**Onset**: 15-30 minutes\n**Duration**: Short-acting (lorazepam 6-12h), long-acting (clonazepam 30-40h)\n**Mechanism**: GABA-A agonist\n**Risks**: Dependence, tolerance, respiratory depression\n**Use**: 2-4 weeks maximum for acute anxiety\n\n## Medical Conditions Causing Anxiety (Differential)\n- Hyperthyroidism\n- Cardiac arrhythmias\n- COPD\n- Caffeine intoxication\n- Medication side effects (stimulants, decongestants)\n\n## Treatment Outcomes\n**CBT response**: 60-70%\n**SSRI response**: 60-70%\n**Combined**: 70-80%\n**Non-response**: Consider other diagnoses, medication optimization\n\n## Special Populations\n**Pregnancy**: SSRIs generally safe, CBT preferred\n**Elderly**: Start low-dose SSRIs, avoid benzodiazepines\n**Adolescents**: Monitor for suicidality with SSRIs\n**Children**: Primarily CBT, medication as adjunct\n\n## Anxiety vs Panic - Key Difference\n**Anxiety**: Sustained worry, anticipatory\n**Panic**: Acute, episodic, peak in 10-20 minutes\n**Agoraphobia**: Fear of places, develops with panic",
